[section 1 Combat]

To attack, choose a weapon to attack with. If it's a ranged weapon, the target
must be within range. If it's a melee weapon, the target must be within reach.

Roll 1d12 and add Dex for accuracy. If the total is greater than or equal to four plus the target's Evd, you hit the target. If you rolled a
natural 12, or equal to or greater than your critical threshold (default 14),
you get a critical hit.

A roll of natural 12 is ALWAYS a hit, and a roll of natural 1 is ALWAYS a
miss. If you roll a natural 1 and you're not Lucky, your weapon takes 1 damage.

Roll your weapon die. If you roll over your attack threshold for that
die, roll again. You deal a number of damage to the target equal to 1 + the number of
re-rolls you've made.

[example Sir Fredrick attacks with a d8/6 longsword. He hits, rolls a 4 on the d8, and deals 1 damage because he didn't re-roll the die. He hits again and rolls a 6 on the d8. Rolling again, he gets a 3. This attack deals 2 damage: 1 + 1 re-roll.]

[example Vargr the Rogue jumps out of an alley and stabs a passing nobleman with his dagger. He rolls a d4/4 for the dagger and a d4/4 for the rogue sneak attack bonus. He gets a 4 and a 2. Re-rolling the 4, he gets a 1. This attack deals 2 damage, because he made one re-roll.]

If you got a critical hit, you can either deal an additional 1 + d8/5 damage;
inflict one point of attribute drain to Str, Dex, Spd, or Con; or deal 1
damage to the target's armor, shield, or weapon.

[section 2 Combat Maneuvers]

If you want to do something special with your attack---push the wight back into
its coffin, shoot the troll's eye out, or break the goblin's kneecaps---you can
take disadvantage (possibly multiple disadvantages, at the GM's discretion) on the
attack roll to pull off your maneuver if the attack hits.

[section 2 Combat Advantages]

[text b Suprise Attacks.] If you attack a creature that doesn't know you're
there, you get a +6 bonus to hit.

[text b Flanking.] If there is an allied creature engaged with your target that
is across from you, you get a +4 bonus to hit.

[text b Mobbing.] For each allied creature engaged with your target, you get a
+1 bonus to hit.

Flanking and mobbing bonuses do not stack---just use whichever is higher.

[section 2 Damage Types]

There is a total of twelve damage types: acid, bludgeoning, cold, fire, holy, lightning, magic, necrotic, piercing, psychic, slashing, and unholy. Every attack has at least one damage type.

Piercing, slashing, and bludgeoning damage all count as physical damage.

Armor is, unless otherwise specified, effective against physical, cold, fire, and acid damage. Whenever a creature suffers damage from an attack with at least one of these damage types, it can roll armor to reduce the damage (see below).

If an equipped armor reduces the damage of an acid attack, the armor takes 1 damage. Some acids may specify what types of material they affect. If a particular acid does not affect the type of material a blocking armor is made of, the armor may remain unharmed.

In the case of attacks that have more than one damage type, use whichever damage
type does the most damage to the target.

Vulnerability to damage doubles the amount of damage taken.

Resistance to damage halves the amount of damage taken.

Immunity to damage reduces the amount of damage taken to 0.

[section 2 PC Defense]

For each incoming damage, roll your Armor die. If the result is equal to or
greater than the armor threshold, you block one damage.

[section 2 Shield Points]

Some effects grant shield points. After rolling for armor, you may spend shield
points to negate an equal amount of damage.

[section 1 Resting and Recovery]

One week of rest provides full recuperation. Healing in any lesser amount of
time requires magic.

Diseases are not automatically cured by resting.

[section 1 Character Death]

When a player character is reduced to 0 health, they fall unconscious until they regain at least
one health. For each damage taken that would bring them below zero health, their Con bonus is instead
permanently reduced by one (with appropriate reductions to health). A character reduced to -4 Con
is irrevocably dead.

