[section 1 Movement]

Every space you move diagonally costs one and a half fathoms of movement.
Round down when determining the total distance you can move.

Moving through difficult terrain costs twice as many movement points as usual.

Some effects use the term "nearby". Nearby can mean 1) anything the GM
determines is nearby, 2) anything within arm's reach, or 3) anything
within one fathom.

[text b A Note on Fathoms.] One fathom is equal to six feet. Six feet is about
the same as 5 feet, which is the standard [dnd] unit of distance. Using fathoms
instead of increments of 5 feet removes the need to divide all distances by
5 to determine the distance in inches/hexes/squares, as well as making movement
speeds a little bit more realistic.

[section 2 Attacks of Opportunity]

If an enemy is wielding a polearm-type weapon with reach, and you move from
outside that enemy's reach to nearby that enemy in a single movement,
that enemy can make a free attack against you, without suffering the penalty
for attacking a nearby target with a reach weapon.

While within reach of an enemy's melee weapon, if you take an action other
than moving or attacking, that enemy may make a free attack against you.

[section 1 Spellcasting]

Exact spellcasting rules differ by class. Some general points about spellcasting
are listed here.

[section 2 Duration]

If the spell has a duration in units of time (rounds, minutes, hours, etc.), it lasts for
a number of units equal to 1d4 + your spell modifier. You can choose to end a spell
at any time.

Spells with a duration of 'concentration' last until you spend an action to attack or cast
another spell. When you take damage, you must succeed on a [check <spellcasting modifier> med]
or the spell ends. 

[section 2 Summoning]

Spells that allow you to summon creatures require knowledge of a summoning ritual.
This ritual consists of an incantation and material components worth a number of
silver coins equal to the creature's rank. These components can be reused.

The ritual takes a number of rounds to perform equal to the rank of the creature.

[section 1 The Turn]

On your turn, you may move a number of fathoms up to your Mv value and take
an action, in either order. You can even interrupt your move with an action.
Possible actions include attacking, casting a spell, checking for traps,
or anything else the GM determines should take an action.

Instead of taking an action, you may move again, up to half your Mv value.

Things like flipping a switch, drawing a weapon, or opening an unlocked door
cost 1 fathom of movement. Speaking is generally free.

